column9: When organizational policies and risk guidelines are followed
column11: Proprietary or patented method (e.g., internal fraud detection algorithm, recommendation engine)
column13: Ethical decision-making systems (e.g., AI-driven hiring tools)
column14: User privacy handling modules (e.g., consent, data collection)
column15: High-availability or safety-critical systems (e.g., medical, aviation)
column16: Comply with data protection regulations (e.g., GDPR, HIPAA, ISO/IEC 27001)
column17: Restrict LLM access to confidential or proprietary business data
column18: Encrypt or anonymize data before sending to LLM
column19: Use on-premises LLMs for sensitive projects instead of cloud-based services.
column20: Organizational approval before using third-party AI tools
column21: Limit copy-paste from AI to avoid licensing/legal issues
column23: Automated security scans and vulnerability testing
column26: Require dual validation: one human reviewer + one automated test pass
column27: Route AI-generated fixes to a separate branch for independent review and testing before merge
column28: Assign credit to the LLM for code contributions
column29: Assign liability if LLM fixes cause damage or failure
column30: Assign responsibility to a human reviewer for reviewing LLM fixes
column31: Document who approved or deployed the LLM-generated fix
column32: Log AI tool usage metadata (prompt, model, timestamp) in version control
column33: Require sign-off from responsible person before merging LLM-generated fixes
column35: Define the types of help taken from LLM
column36: Require LLM to provide reasoning behind their suggested fixes.
column38: In-code labeling to flag AI-generated logic/code
column39: Mandatory LLM disclosure note in commit messages
column40: Purpose & Scope - What the LLM is used for and its limitations
column41: Code Contribution - What parts were AI-generated, including liability and credit
column42: Data Handling - Specify how data is collected, stored, and processed
column43: Model explanation - Description of how the AI model produced the fix (e.g., logic, reasoning, or influencing factors)
column44: Ethical Standards - Steps taken to ensure fairness and avoid discrimination
column45: Governance and Accountability - Define oversight roles and responsibilities for LLM management
column46: Justification or intention - Why the AI tool was used
column47: Validation level - How thoroughly the AI-generated fix was reviewed or tested
column49: Version Control - Commit messages, diffs, or pull request summaries
column50: User Documentation - Manuals, FAQs, or product help sections
column51: Developer Dashboards - Logs or summaries tracking AI-generated code by developer each session
column52: Stakeholder Meetings - Presentations to partners, users, or clients
column53: Regulatory Filings - Reports submitted for compliance/legal needs
column54: Method/ Class Level Code Documentation - Before each method/class, document types of help taken from LLM, liability%, credit%, and risk level
column55: In-line Code Comments - Mark specific lines where LLM contributed (e.g., // generated by Copilot)
